# [ANRW](../wg/anrw.html)

## Summary

The second slot of the Applied Networking Research Workshop (ANRW) featured presentations on security and privacy. The session was chaired by Georg Carle. Five talks were scheduled, covering topics such as privacy disparities in proxy infrastructures, zero-shot IoT device labeling, algebraic frameworks for source address validation, the real-world state of Discovery of Designated Resolvers (DDR) deployment, and the performance of DNS over QUIC in Indian access networks. 

---

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Unequal Cover: Measuring Privacy Disparities in Proxy Infrastructure
* **Presenter:** Paul Schmidt
* **Slides:** [Security and Privacy - Unequal cover](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-security-and-privacy-unequal-cover-00)
* **Discussion:**
    * Paul Schmidt presented a study evaluating whether multi-party relays (MPRs), such as Apple's iCloud Private Relay, provide equitable geolocation privacy to all users. 
    * The study modeled US user populations using census tract data to analyze "crowd sizes" (the anonymity set of users sharing an egress IP prefix).
    * Results indicated a significant digital divide: rural tracts have a 9.3x smaller median crowd size compared to urban areas. Furthermore, in rural areas, lower-income tracts experience even smaller crowd sizes, creating a compounding disadvantage.
    * A simulation demonstrated that iteratively removing approximately 19% of the smallest egresses and reassigning users to the next nearest egress could increase the median crowd size by 2.5x with only a minor increase in average physical distance to the egress point.
    * **Q&A:**
        * **Tommy Pauly** asked if the adoption rate used was based on empirical measurements. Paul Schmidt clarified that the study assumed a uniform 0.11% adoption rate based on APNIC data, though they also simulated income-weighted adoption which showed even greater inequality. 
        * Tommy Pauly noted that iCloud Private Relay has a mode allowing users to choose country/time-zone level granularity, which would naturally expand the anonymity set, and suggested that investigating international disparities would be valuable.

### 2. Zero-Shot IoT Device Type Labeling
* **Presenter:** Vered Shwartz
* **Slides:** [Security and Privacy - Zero-Shot IoT Device Type Labeling](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-security-and-privacy-zero-shot-iot-device-type-labeling-00)
* **Discussion:**
    * Vered Shwartz presented "Zelle" (ZIL), a passive, zero-shot system designed to label previously unseen IoT devices (identifying vendor and function) without requiring prior training samples.
    * The system extracts local network telemetry clues (such as hostnames, domains, and MAC addresses) and enriches them via search engines to gather context from user manuals, blogs, and documentation. It then performs vendor and function labeling using a specialized zero-shot classification model (Roberta) alongside a curated IoT catalog.
    * Zelle achieved 86% accuracy on vendor labeling and up to 81% accuracy on function labeling in real-world wild datasets.
    * **Q&A:**
        * **Suresh Krishnan** asked if the system could leverage Manufacturer Usage Description (MUD) files to improve classification accuracy. Vered Shwartz indicated that incorporating additional metadata like MUD is a viable path.
        * **Stuart Cheshire** highlighted the inherent tension between user privacy (anonymizing devices) and local network management (the need to identify devices for security). He questioned how encryption trends might impact the system. Vered Shwartz replied that the system is designed to operate behind firewalls that perform decryption and noted that future work would address identifying devices hidden behind NATs or hubs.

### 3. An Algebraic Framework for Source Address Validation
* **Presenter:** Libin Yu
* **Slides:** [Security and Privacy - An Algebraic Framework for Source Address Validation](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-security-an-algebraic-framework-for-source-address-validation-01)
* **Discussion:**
    * Libin Yu introduced SavA, an algebraic framework designed to unify diverse source address validation (SAV) mechanisms—such as strict/loose uRPF, enhanced feasible uRPF (EFeURPF), and SAVNET—under a single mathematical formulation.
    * By treating SAV as monotone operators on a finite complete lattice, the framework provides the first formal mathematical proofs for convergence, correctness, and performance of SAV state propagation.
    * Evaluations using real-world topologies showed 100% correctness agreement across test families, showing how incremental deployment (e.g., 20% deployment of SAVNET) can block up to 98.3% of spoofed traffic.
    * **Q&A:**
        * **Suresh Krishnan** welcomed the research and highlighted its direct relevance to the active work in the IETF SAVNET working group.

### 4. The Illusion of DDR Deployment
* **Presenter:** Yevgenia
* **Slides:** [Security and Privacy - The Illusion of DDR Deployment](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-security-and-privacy-the-illusion-of-ddr-deployment-00)
* **Discussion:**
    * Yevgenia presented an update on the deployment of Discovery of Designated Resolvers (DDR). 
    * While active scanning initially identified approximately 300,000 open resolvers returning DDR records, over 90% of these returned records belonged to major public resolvers like Google and Cloudflare rather than the local resolver.
    * By cross-referencing with a dedicated forwarder detection scan, the study confirmed that these incorrect configurations are caused by transparent forwarders. These forwarders incorrectly pass queries for `_dns.resolver.arpa` upstream instead of handling them locally as mandated by the RFC.
    * The study concluded that only about 900 open resolvers globally have correctly implemented and deployed DDR.
    * **Q&A:**
        * **Marco Davids** shared difficulties in configuring local open resolvers to trigger automatic client transitions to encrypted DNS. Yevgenia noted that her research did not evaluate client-side transition behavior directly.
        * **Tommy Pauly** asked if the scanning setup could detect networks that actively block or drop DDR discovery queries. Yevgenia answered that the current scan setup cannot determine path-blocking.
        * A **Firefox Representative** commented that Firefox is currently implementing DDR and noted that these deployment insights are highly valuable for ensuring certificate validation matches.
        * A researcher from the Hasso Plattner Institute confirmed that their independent research yielded similar findings regarding the prevalence of transparent forwarders.

### 5. QUIC Meets Reality
* **Presenters:** Lohit Karyala (curtailed due to audio issues) and Jayshree
* **Slides:** [Security and Privacy - QUIC Meets Reality](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-security-and-privacy-quic-meets-reality-00)
* **Discussion:**
    * The presentation evaluated the real-world deployment and performance of QUIC-based encrypted DNS protocols, specifically DNS-over-QUIC (DoQ) and DNS-over-HTTP/3 (DoH3), across major Indian access networks (Airtel, Jio, and university Wi-Fi).
    * Out of 28 validated encrypted DNS resolvers discovered in India, 20 supported DoH, 13 supported DoQ, and only 2 supported DoH3. The transition to QUIC-based DNS remains largely incomplete in the region, with deployments concentrated primarily in western and southern India.
    * **Q&A:**
        * **Suresh Krishnan** noted that the study relied on a single vantage point. Jayshree acknowledged this limitation and confirmed that expanding measurements to multiple distinct vantage points is part of their planned future work.

